          "body": "The chapter opens with a superscription that is itself theologically loaded: 'the word of the LORD to Jeremiah in regard to the drought.' The drought is not merely a meteorological event narrated for pastoral sympathy — it is a word. God is speaking through cracked ground, empty cisterns, shamed farmers, an abandoned fawn, and panting wild donkeys. Deuteronomy 28:23-24 had warned that covenant disobedience would turn the sky to bronze and the earth to iron, withholding rain. What Jeremiah describes in 14:2-6 is precisely that covenant curse arriving in vivid detail. The descent through the social hierarchy — nobles who send servants (14:3), farmers who cover their heads in shame (14:4), and then animals who cannot instinctively care for their young (14:5-6) — maps the total reach of the judgment. When even the doe in the field abandons her fawn for lack of grass, the created order itself is testifying to covenantal rupture. Swindoll notes in his Jeremiah commentary that the prophet is given the rare task of narrating suffering that God Himself has authorized — making the description not a complaint against God but a case study in what covenant faithlessness ultimately produces."
