          "body": "Verses 17-18 pivot the chapter's emotional register from juridical verdict to pastoral lament. God commissions Jeremiah to weep — 'let my eyes flow down with tears night and day, and let them not cease' — a command that reveals something about the divine heart behind the judgment. The tears are not optional sentiment but prophetic duty: the prophet's body must embody the grief that God carries over the devastation He has decreed. The image of 'the virgin daughter of my people' crushed by a 'mighty blow' and a 'sorely infected wound' (14:17) positions Judah as innocent in metaphor precisely when she is guilty in fact — not to excuse the sin, but to capture the tragedy of a people destroyed by consequences they chose. When Jeremiah goes out to the countryside, he sees the sword-slain; when he enters the city, he sees the famine-ravaged (14:18). There is no angle from which the view is not catastrophic. The closing image — 'both prophet and priest have gone roving about in a land they do not know' — is a damning summary of religious leadership's failure. The leaders who should have known God and known the land are exposed as disoriented wanderers. Calvin noted on this passage that pastoral grief is itself a form of intercession — when words are refused, tears carry what the prayer could not."
